  "prompt": "Can all engines be overbored? What engines cannot be overbored?",
  "response": "Not all engines can be overbored, and whether or not an engine can be overbored depends on several factors. Overboring refers to increasing the diameter of an engine's cylinders to accommodate larger pistons, which can help improve engine performance by increasing displacement. However, there are limitations and considerations for overboring, as follows:\n\n### Factors Influencing Overboring Capability\n\n1. **Engine Material and Design:**\n   - **Construction Material:** Engines made of cast iron typically have more material to work with compared to aluminum engines, which can be more sensitive to overboring.\n   - **Engine Design:** Some engine designs, particularly those with thin cylinder walls or integrated cylinder barrels (like two-stroke engines), may not have enough material to safely accommodate a larger bore.\n\n2. **Cylinder Wall Thickness:**\n   - Every engine has a minimum safe wall thickness after overboring is performed. If the walls become too thin, the engine may be prone to overheating, cracking, or failure.\n\n3. **Block Wear:**\n   - Engines that are already worn or have significant existing damage may not be suitable for overboring, as the structural integrity may be compromised.\n\n4. **Availability of Oversize Pistons:**\n   - Even if the engine could theoretically be overbored, the availability of matching oversize pistons is critical. If oversize pistons are not available, overboring may not be feasible.\n\n5. **Engine Type:**\n   - Certain engine types, such as rotary engines (like the Mazda Wankel), have unique considerations that make traditional overboring impractical.\n\n### Engines Typically Not Suitable for Overboring\n\n1. **Short-Block and Closed Deck Engines:**\n   - Engines with closed deck designs (where cylinder walls are closely surrounded by the block) might not allow for sufficient overboring due to limited material.\n\n2. **Two-Stroke Engines:**\n   - Two-stroke engines often have fewer design allowances for overboring, especially those with integral cylinders.\n\n3. **High-Performance Engines:**\n   - Some high-performance or factory-tuned engines are designed with specific tolerances and may not have the flexibility for boring without affecting performance.\n\n4. **Engines with Thin Wall Castings:**\n   - Any engine with castings that are extremely thin or that have been previously machined may not be candidates for overboring due to the risk of structural weakness.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nIn summary, while many engines can be overbored, there are significant limitations and considerations that must be assessed before proceeding. An engine that is suitable for overboring should have adequate cylinder wall thickness, be free from excessive wear or damage, and ideally be designed with a focus on possible adjustments. Always consult with a qualified engine builder or machinist before undertaking any modifications to ensure safety and maintain performance.",
